description:
QUICK BACKGROUND: 
Itâs from the Apiaceae family which includes carrots, fennel, and parsley; it can be mistaken for such plants. When blooming, poison hemlock have white flowers while fennel have yellow flowers. It is a non-native and invasive plant in California.


GROWTH FORM:
- herb
- when young, it looks like a carrot plant


IDENTIFYING CHARACTERISTICS:
- stem: splotchy purple stems, no hair, hollow
- leaves: lobed, compound, alternate
- flowers: white flowers (at the time this plant was identified, the plant wasnât blooming)


WHERE DOES IT GROW?: 
As long as there is enough water, poison hemlock can thrive in dry and wet places. The particular plant we saw grew near a river.


SIGNIFICANCE:
- poisonous!! All parts of the plant are poisonous, itâs even irritating to touch
- culturally significant: itâs what Socrates drank as poison to end his life
- ecologically significant: itâs poisonous to humans and cattle (animals) & itâs an invasive species
